\par }{\cf0 WHAT IS A PLANE?
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The planes of existence are different realities with interwoven connections. Except for rare linking points, each plane is effectively its own universe with its own natural laws. 
\par }\pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 The planes break down into a number of general type
s: the Material Plane, the Transitive Planes, the Inner Planes, the Outer Planes, and the demiplanes.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Material Plane: }{\fs20\cf0 
The Material Plane tends to be the most Earthlike of all planes and operates under the same set of natural laws that our own real world does. This is the default plane for most adventures.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Transitive Planes:}{\fs20\cf0  These three planes have one important common 
characteristic: Each is used to get from one place to another. The Astral Plane is a conduit to all other planes, while the Ethereal Plane and the Plane of Shadow both serve as means of transportation within the Material Plane they\rquote 
re connected to. These planes have the strongest regular interaction with the Material Plane and are often accessed by using various spells. They have native inhabitants as well.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Inner Planes:}{\fs20\cf0  These six planes are manifestations of the basic building blocks of the universe. Each 
is made up of a single type of energy or element that overwhelms all others. The natives of a particular Inner Plane are made of the same energy or element as the plane itself.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Outer Planes:}{\fs20\cf0  The deities live on the Outer Planes, as do creatures such as cel
estials, demons, and devils. Each of the Outer Planes has an alignment, representing a particular moral or ethical outlook, and the natives of each plane tend to behave in agreement with that plane\rquote 
s alignment. The Outer Planes are also the final resting place of souls from the Material Plane, whether that final rest takes the form of calm introspection or eternal damnation.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Demiplanes:}{\fs20\cf0  This catch-all category covers all extradimensional spaces that function like planes but have measurable size and limited 
access. Other kinds of planes are theoretically infinite in size, but a demiplane might be only a few hundred feet across.
\par }{\fs18\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 PLANAR TRAITS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Each plane of existence has its own properties\emdash the natural laws of its universe.
\par Planar traits are broken down into a number of general areas.
\par 
\par All planes have the following kinds of traits.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Physical Traits:}{\fs20\cf0  These traits determine the laws of physics and nature on the plane, including how gravity and time function.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Elemental and Energy Traits:}{\fs20\cf0  These traits determine the dominance of particular elemental or energy forces.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Alignment Traits:}{\fs20\cf0  Just as characters may be lawful neutral or chaotic good, many planes are tied to a particular moral or ethical outlook.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Magic Traits:}{\fs20\cf0  Magic works differently from plane to plane, and magic traits set the boundaries for what it can and can\rquote t do.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel0\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b0\fs24 Physical Traits
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
The two most important natural laws set by physical traits are how gravity works and how time passes. Other physical traits pertain to the size and shape of a plane and how easily a plane\rquote s nature can be altered.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Gravity:}{\fs20\cf0  The direction of gravity\rquote s pull may be unusual, and it might even change directions within the plane itself.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Normal Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 Most planes have gravity similar to that of the Material Plane. The usual rules fo
r ability scores, carrying capacity, and encumbrance apply. Unless otherwise noted in a description, it is assumed every plane has the normal gravity trait.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Heavy Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 The gravity on a plane with this trait is much more intense than on the Material Plane. As a result, Balance, Climb, Jump, Ride, Swim, and Tumble checks incur a \endash 
2 circumstance penalty, as do all attack rolls. All item weights are effectively doubled, which might affect a character\rquote s speed. Weapon ranges are halved. A character\rquote s Strength
 and Dexterity scores are not affected. Characters who fall on a heavy gravity plane take 1d10 points of damage for each 10 feet fallen, to a maximum of 20d10 points of damage.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Light Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 The gravity on a plane with this trait is less intense than on t
he Material Plane. As a result, creatures find that they can lift more, but their movements tend to be ungainly. Characters on a plane with the light gravity trait take a \endash 
2 circumstance penalty on attack rolls and Balance, Ride, Swim, and Tumble checks. All items weigh half as much. Weapon ranges double, and characters gain a +2 circumstance bonus on Climb and Jump checks.
\par Strength and Dexterity don\rquote t change as a result of light gravity, but what you can do with such scores does change. These advantages apply to travelers from other planes as well as natives.
\par Falling characters on a light gravity plane take 1d4 points of damage for each 10 feet of the fall (maximum 20d4).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 No Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 Individuals on a plane with this trait merely float in space, unless other resources are available to provide a direction for gravity\rquote s pull.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Objective Directional Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 The strength of gravity on a plane with this trait is the same as on the Material Plane, but the direction is not the traditional \'93down\'94 toward the ground. I
t may be down toward any solid object, at an angle to the surface of the plane itself, or even upward.
\par In addition, objective directional gravity may change from place to place. The direction of \'93down\'94 may vary.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Subjective Directional Gravity: }{\fs20\cf0 The strength of gravity on a plane with this trait is the same as on the Material Plane, but each individual chooses the direction of gravity\rquote 
s pull. Such a plane has no gravity for unattended objects and nonsentient creatures. This sort of environment can be very disorienting to the newcomer, but is common on \'93weightless\'94 planes.
\par Characters on a plane with subjective directional gravity can move normally along a solid surface by imagining \'93down\'94 near their feet. If suspended in midair, a character \'93flies\'94 by merely choosing a \'93down\'94 direction and \'93falling\'94
 that way. Under such a procedure, an individual \'93falls\'94 150 feet in the first round and 300 feet in each succeeding round. Movement is straight-line only. In order to stop, one has to slow one\rquote s movement by changing the designated \'93down
\'94 direction (again, moving 150 feet in the new direction in the first round and 300 feet per round thereafter).
\par It takes a DC 16 Wisdom check to set a new direction of gravity as a free action; this check can be made once per round. Any character who fails this Wisdom check in successive rounds receives a +6 bonus on subsequent checks until he or she succeeds.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Time:}{\fs20\cf0  The rate of time\rquote s passage can vary on different planes, though it remains constant within any particular plane. Time is a
lways subjective for the viewer. The same subjectivity applies to various planes. Travelers may discover that they\rquote ll pick up or lose time while moving among the planes, but from their point of view, time always passes naturally.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Normal Time: }{\fs20\cf0 This trait de
scribes the way time passes on the Material Plane. One hour on a plane with normal time equals one hour on the Material Plane. Unless otherwise noted in a description, every plane has the normal time trait.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Timeless: }{\fs20\cf0 On planes with this trait, time still p
asses, but the effects of time are diminished. How the timeless trait can affect certain activities or conditions such as hunger, thirst, aging, the effects of poison, and healing varies from plane to plane.
\par The danger of a timeless plane is that once one leaves such a plane for one where time flows normally, conditions such as hunger and aging do occur retroactively. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Flowing Time: }{\fs20\cf0 On some planes, time can flow faster or slower. One may travel to another plane, spend a year there, then return to the Materi
al Plane to find that only six seconds have elapsed. Everything on the plane returned to is only a few seconds older. But for that traveler and the items, spells, and effects working on him, that year away was entirely real.
\par When designating how time works on planes with flowing time, put the Material Plane\rquote s flow of time first, followed by the same flow in the other plane. 
